{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636829"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:34:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:34:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17606"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17606"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0,0.78,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71549"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10320"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17606"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57038"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10036"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24142"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71549"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe digestion of dietary lipids in the small intestine involves multiple coordinated processes. Bile salts have an important role during lipid digestion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes their primary function during lipid digestion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of chylomicrons","Transport of fatty acids across cell membranes","Emulsification of dietary lipids","Activation of digestive enzymes","Hydrolysis of triglycerides"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe main function of bile salts is \u003Cstrong\u003Eemulsification of dietary lipids\u003C/strong\u003E. Their amphipathic structure allows them to break down large fat droplets into smaller ones, increasing the surface area available for digestive enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of chylomicrons\u003C/strong\u003E occurs inside enterocytes after lipid absorption is complete\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport of fatty acids across cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E involves specific protein transporters and passive diffusion\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of digestive enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily achieved by other molecules such as colipase\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrolysis of triglycerides\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by pancreatic lipase, not bile salts\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe physical process of emulsification by bile salts creates optimal conditions for subsequent enzymatic digestion of dietary fats. Without this step, lipid digestion would be severely impaired.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bile salts are amphipathic molecules that break down large fat droplets into smaller ones through emulsification","The emulsification process increases the surface area available for digestive enzyme action","Efficient fat digestion requires both physical emulsification by bile salts and enzymatic breakdown by lipases"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"